# Critical extraction note: zbg uses **OCaml
# Jane Street `let%map_open.Command` PPX syntax
# extension CLI pattern** at cli.ml:16-21+ —
# `(let%map_open.Command force = flag "f"
# ~aliases:[ "--force" ] no_arg ~doc:"..." in
# fun () -> Git.clear (to_force_flag force))`.
# `let%map_open` is a PPX SYNTAX EXTENSION
# (provided by `ppx_let` package) that desugars
# to APPLICATIVE composition: each `let%map_open.
# Command X = SPEC` clause binds `X` to the
# parsed value (extracted applicatively from
# the SPEC).  Multiple `and X2 = SPEC2` clauses
# can extend the binding.  Distinct from R270
# Haskell optparse-applicative (`<$>` and `<*>`
# applicative ops explicitly), R322 JCommander
# annotation-based, R325 OCaml stdlib Arg
# (mutable ref-cell binding).  Jane Street's
# approach: PPX SYNTAX EXTENSION for applicative
# composition — corpus's **first documented
# let-map-open-PPX-applicative CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: zbg uses **OCaml
# Jane Street `flag "NAME" ~aliases:[LIST]
# ARG_SHAPE ~doc:"..."` flag-function CLI
# pattern** at cli.ml:18+ — `flag "f" ~aliases:
# ["--force"] no_arg ~doc:"..."`.  `flag` is a
# function returning `Param.t<T>` where T is
# determined by the ARG-SHAPE FUNCTION.  Arg
# shapes: `no_arg` (boolean), `string` /`int`/
# `bool` (typed value), `optional X` (zero-or-
# one), `listed X` (zero-or-more), `escape`
# (collect remaining argv).  `~aliases`,
# `~doc`, `~full_flag_required`, etc. are
# OCaml LABELLED ARGUMENTS (keyword args).
# Distinct from R325 OCaml stdlib `Arg.Set
# ref_bool` (spec variants), R322 JCommander
# `@Parameter(names = arrayOf(...))`
# annotation, R311 Guile `(NAME (single-char
# #\X) (value #t/#f))` quoted alist.  Jane
# Street's approach: `flag NAME ~aliases:LIST
# ARG_SHAPE_FUNC ~doc:"..."` with LABELLED
# ARGS — corpus's **first documented flag-
# function-with-arg-shape-function CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: zbg uses **OCaml
# Jane Street `anon ("NAME" %: TYPE)` `%:` type-
# assignment-operator CLI pattern** at cli.ml:
# 26+ — `anon (sequence ("message" %: string))`,
# `anon (maybe_with_default "HEAD" ("commit"
# %: string))`, `anon ("tag_name" %: string)`.
# `%:` is the TYPE ASSIGNMENT OPERATOR binding
# the positional NAME to its TYPE CONVERTER.
# Builtin converters: `string`, `int`, `bool`,
# `float`, `file` (file path with completion),
# `date` (Date.t), `time` (Time.t), `host_and_
# port` (Host_and_port.t).  Custom converters
# via `Command.Arg_type.create FN`.  Distinct
# from R325 OCaml stdlib Arg (anon-fun callback
# for positionals — no type associated), R270
# Haskell `argument str (metavar "FILE")`, R272
# C POSIX (argv[i] post-parse).  Jane Street's
# approach: `%:` TYPE-ASSIGNMENT OPERATOR
# coupling NAME and TYPE in one expression —
# corpus's **first documented `%:`-type-
# assignment-operator CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: zbg uses **OCaml
# Jane Street anonymous-positional combinators
# `maybe`/`maybe_with_default`/`sequence`/
# `non_empty_sequence_as_list` CLI pattern** at
# cli.ml:35, 41, 60, 75 — `anon (maybe_with_
# default "HEAD" ("commit" %: string))`, `anon
# (non_empty_sequence_as_list ("description"
# %: string))`, `anon (sequence ("message" %:
# string))`, `anon (maybe ("branch" %: string))`.
# These are positional MULTIPLICITY COMBINATORS:
#   `maybe`            ← zero or one (Option)
#   `maybe_with_default V` ← zero or one (default V)
#   `sequence`         ← zero or more (list)
#   `non_empty_sequence_as_list` ← one or more
#                                 (list)
#   `escape`           ← collect ALL remaining
#                        argv as STRING LIST
# Distinct from R330 Rust bpaf `.optional()`/
# `.many()` (method-chain), R270 Haskell
# `optional`/`many` (applicative ops).  Jane
# Street's approach: ANONYMOUS-POSITIONAL
# COMBINATORS as FUNCTION CALLS — corpus's
# **first documented function-call-positional-
# multiplicity-combinator CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: zbg uses **OCaml
# Jane Street `Command.group ~summary:"..."
# [(NAME, CMD); ...]` list-of-pairs-subcommand
# CLI pattern** at cli.ml:99-114 — `Command.
# group ~summary:"Easier git workflow"
# [("clear", cmd_clear); ("commit", cmd_
# commit); ("done", cmd_done); ...]`.  Each
# command is itself a `Command.basic` or
# `Command.group` (recursive nesting).  The
# user dispatches via `zbg SUBCOMMAND ARGS`.
# Distinct from R322 JCommander `commands =>
# #{}` (Erlang map), R302 babashka.cli `[:cmds
# ["sub"]]` (vector tag), R325 OCaml stdlib
# Arg (no subcommand support — caller routes
# manually).  Jane Street's approach: `Command.
# group ~summary [(NAME, CMD); ...]` LIST-OF-
# PAIRS for subcommands — corpus's **first
# documented list-of-name-command-pairs
# subcommand CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: zbg uses **OCaml
# Jane Street `Command.Param.return ACTION`
# no-arg-command CLI pattern** at cli.ml:31, 65,
# 96, 97 — `let cmd_done = Command.basic
# ~summary:"..." (Command.Param.return Git.
# done_)`.  `Command.Param.return ACTION` is
# the IDENTITY applicative — produces a Param
# that always succeeds and returns ACTION
# without consuming any args.  Used for
# subcommands that take NO ARGUMENTS.
# Distinct from R325 OCaml stdlib Arg (no
# direct equivalent — caller checks `Arg.
# parse` results), R270 Haskell `pure FUNC`
# applicative return.  Jane Street's approach:
# `Command.Param.return` AS IDENTITY APPLICATIVE
# — corpus's **first documented Param.return-
# no-arg-command CLI pattern**.
